00:53:46,603 --> 00:53:50,569
Patrick: Patrick [00:53:47]: What do you think the most mis-valued asset in the world is today?

540
00:53:50,569 --> 00:53:58,220
Charlie: Charlie [00:53:51]: I would say it's probably entrepreneurs in markets that are non-obvious.

541
00:53:58,629 --> 00:54:01,129
And I don't mean because their end market is not obvious.

542
00:54:01,220 --> 00:54:10,969
It's people addressing global problems, but in some secondary city in Romania, because capital markets at that stage, are just not efficient enough to find them.

543
00:54:10,969 --> 00:54:12,550
There's a famous company, UI path.

544
00:54:12,550 --> 00:54:15,060
I think now worth about 10 billion, that came out of Romania.

545
00:54:15,120 --> 00:54:17,229
And so there's a dramatic example of that.

546
00:54:17,650 --> 00:54:21,560
I think if you were to say, well, where is there a core option?

547
00:54:21,620 --> 00:54:23,549
It's probably something in crypto.

548
00:54:24,090 --> 00:54:25,840
It may exist or it may not exist.

549
00:54:25,950 --> 00:54:33,930
I think one of the great questions is, is everything in that space now in the Lycos/Alta Vista high cost space or is it at the Google and Amazon stage?

550
00:54:34,180 --> 00:54:52,150
That's a very hard question to answer in foresight, irritating obvious in hindsight, but it does seem there's a probability mass of something being very big there because there's something about finance where it's demarcated by nation state, even though it's a pure electronic good.

551
00:54:52,330 --> 00:55:07,159
And so, anything that's just pure numbers in the sky should actually be globally scalable, but it isn't because of the existing finance regulatory environment and the existing historical paths, sort of banks when they were physical institutions.

552
00:55:07,340 --> 00:55:14,640
That makes me think this globalization of finance has the potential for multiple trillion dollar market cap companies over the next decades.

553
00:55:15,710 --> 00:55:19,100
Patrick: Patrick [00:55:15]: You mentioned Romania, which just makes me think of Europe more broadly speaking.

554
00:55:19,150 --> 00:55:23,759
I'd be curious your relative take on opportunity in Europe for business and investing.

555
00:55:23,840 --> 00:55:29,180
When the last decade has been relatively underwhelming, certainly relative to the performance of us companies.

556
00:55:29,730 --> 00:55:38,100
Charlie: Charlie [00:55:30]: It is amazing that if you look at the top 10, maybe even the top 20 by now, companies in the world by market cap, they're exclusively US and China.

557
00:55:38,710 --> 00:55:41,420
That’s an absolutely fascinating stats and says so much about the last 10 years.

558
00:55:41,670 --> 00:55:52,040
There's a very sort of dark line of thought, which says one of the best things about Europe is that you probably have a less geopolitical risk than any other place.

559
00:55:52,230 --> 00:56:00,294
There's something about the horrors of Somme, Verdun and Stalingrad that makes it some unimaginable for Germany and France to have a conflict.

560
00:56:00,294 --> 00:56:07,170
Whereas, as I think it is much more imaginable to have China, India, US those sort of countries have conflict.

561
00:56:07,240 --> 00:56:13,870
So in some ways, one of the things you have in Europe is a sort of absence of systemic risk of wipe out.

562
00:56:14,099 --> 00:56:17,939
Because if you look at what really destroys investing returns, it's geopolitical conflict.

563
00:56:18,050 --> 00:56:24,630
If you look at the collapse of European wealth in World War One, World War Two, it's just absolutely epic.

564
00:56:24,630 --> 00:56:27,665
And I think that may be an under-priced benefit of Europe.

565
00:56:27,840 --> 00:56:44,640
I think the other much more cheerful and practical one, is there are countries with institutions weren't developed enough to build a Google, arguably that's every other country apart from the US, but I think it is certainly true of very small European countries because they just don't have the complexity of legal system.

566
00:56:44,860 --> 00:56:47,150
They don't obviously have a means of going public.

567
00:56:47,300 --> 00:56:51,370
They don't have the institutional norms or the depth of financing or anything like that.

568
00:56:51,520 --> 00:57:04,480
But now I see so many companies come out of Europe that are Delaware corporations LLCs, that have say West Coast investors, the legal documents by Wilson Sonsini or some other US firm.

569
00:57:04,480 --> 00:57:28,340
And you have this amazing mix of sort of Soviet quality education, which is very high in math and logic, post-Soviet GDP per head, which basically means your capital goes very far, but with US high trust institutions acting to sort of scale it to the corporation and that unique coming together, feels special.

570
00:57:29,070 --> 00:57:30,799
Patrick: Patrick [00:57:29]: It's a fascinating take on everything.

571
00:57:30,799 --> 00:57:37,560
I mean, I had never considered really any of those angles, again appealing to the 483 companies that you've invested in.

572
00:57:37,600 --> 00:57:41,100
I'd love to know the geographic dispersion of those things generally speaking,

573
00:57:41,680 --> 00:57:57,030
Charlie: Charlie [00:57:41]: Almost an even mix between US, UK, continental Europe would account for 90% with the remaining 10% scattered in Asia, Africa, Latin America, with the particular hub in Singapore, because of an incubator called Entrepreneurs First that I invest in with a great deal.

574
00:57:57,030 --> 00:57:57,423
Patrick: Patrick [00:57:57]: Yeah.

575
00:57:57,590 --> 00:57:59,960
I've had Matt on the show, which was a fantastic episode.

576
00:58:00,010 --> 00:58:02,480
I love his idea of the history of the technology of ambition.

577
00:58:03,200 --> 00:58:10,060
Charlie: Charlie [00:58:03]: It's completely Matt's IP, which was, it's very interesting to think where talented people go as a framework.

578
00:58:10,230 --> 00:58:15,610
And so, if you go back and go the other way and say, what can you learn from investing when you look at history.

579
00:58:15,700 --> 00:58:27,920
It's interesting to think what is underestimated because of the decline of some institution, not all the stuff people think about when they wrote about it, but just that very talented people who are young chose to go a different direction.

580
00:58:28,379 --> 00:58:34,540
So there was a time when you're a young man and you can choose, do I go and do an administration of a Roman province?

581
00:58:34,810 --> 00:58:36,380
Or do I join the early Christian church?

582
00:58:36,600 --> 00:58:41,839
Possibly the talent started to flow towards the church and away from Roman institutions and that actually caused a weakening.

583
00:58:41,980 --> 00:58:46,159
That is a generalized framework of where exceptional talent choose to go is super interesting.

584
00:58:46,320 --> 00:59:01,089
So one thought that occurs in our world is perhaps the sort of investment banks and consulting firms and law firms of tomorrow will be much less good than their precursors 20, 30 years ago, because so many talented people are going into entrepreneurship and that talent has to pull out of somewhere.

585
00:59:01,280 --> 00:59:16,210
Now, I think again, from a sort of societal viewpoint, I think putting talented people, in things that can scale their products to millions of people is higher utility than putting them in effectively in a high end artisan perfection like consulting or the law where the output doesn't scale.

586
00:59:16,210 --> 00:59:16,213
[Information Curation]

587
00:59:16,213 --> 00:59:24,190
Patrick: Patrick [00:59:16]: It seems to me that a lot of what you're doing with your life and career is curation of people, ideas, companies, history.

588
00:59:24,190 --> 00:59:26,510
I mean so many different examples in our conversation today.

589
00:59:26,590 --> 00:59:36,200
I'd love you to riff on that idea of curation and whether or not it's going to become an increasingly important skill in a world that is exploding with information and content and data.

590
00:59:37,149 --> 00:59:44,000
Charlie: Charlie [00:59:37]: Very simply as if you think back to sort of 30 years ago, your basic problem is lack of information.

591
00:59:44,230 --> 00:59:51,290
So you sort of read about capital markets investors in the 1990s, and they are reading SEC filings, reading sell side reports.

592
00:59:51,420 --> 00:59:55,244
They're trying to get time with management, but it's a fundamental lack of information problem.

593
00:59:55,244 --> 00:59:55,805
[“If you hang out with people smarter, harder working, and morally better than oneself, you always live in a funnel of positive serendipity because effectively you are dragged upwards to the mean benchmark, which is higher than oneself.”]

594
00:59:55,820 --> 01:00:02,010
Now you look at the massive growth of available information, and I think it becomes much more of a filtering problem.

595
01:00:02,270 --> 01:00:11,060
And in some ways, the best way to filter is to have second stage filters before your filter, which is just to find amazing people and use them as filter points.

596
01:00:11,340 --> 01:00:28,240
So there's a sort of phase, which is: “if you hang out with people smarter, harder working, and morally better than oneself, you always live in a funnel of positive serendipity because effectively you are dragged upwards to the mean benchmark, which is higher than oneself.” So that's what I try to do.

597
01:00:28,240 --> 01:00:30,589
Patrick: Patrick [01:00:29]: You just described my whole life.

598
01:00:30,639 --> 01:00:34,270
I'm playing with this idea now of it's better to be interested than interesting.

599
01:00:34,350 --> 01:00:40,859
And if someone that's never been particularly interesting, a great way to eventually become interesting is to be purely interested all the time.

600
01:00:40,859 --> 01:00:41,870
Charlie: Charlie [01:00:41]: Yes.

601
01:00:41,960 --> 01:00:42,790
A hundred percent.

602
01:00:42,860 --> 01:00:54,349
And I think Patrick, if you could overlay amazing people in a unique configuration, you get an information for you that is both a accretive to you, it pulls you up, but it's also a unique lens in the world.

603
01:00:54,490 --> 01:00:56,962
And from unique lenses, you get unique opportunities.

604
01:00:56,962 --> 01:00:58,190
Patrick: Patrick [01:00:57]: By that.

605
01:00:58,190 --> 01:01:03,420
Do you just mean non-overlapping kind of backgrounds and areas of interest in the people in your network?

606
01:01:03,870 --> 01:01:04,200
Charlie: Charlie [01:01:03]: Yeah.

607
01:01:04,200 --> 01:01:09,259
And one of the ones that I think is always fascinates me is just have geographically disparate networks.

608
01:01:09,480 --> 01:01:16,310
Often you get these very sort of tight communities in some ways, the Valley, in some ways, sort of New York, say the hedge fund community.

609
01:01:16,770 --> 01:01:26,030
Sometimes the most obvious insights are just from going between one to the other and just seeing the difference in worldviews in stark relief from each other.

610
01:01:26,190 --> 01:01:28,199
And so I sort of think about that constantly.

611
01:01:28,199 --> 01:01:40,000
I mean, one of the ones that's most powerful is just imagine thinking about the same problem, not from a US perspective, but from say a Finnish perspective on our Albanian perspective.

612
01:01:40,090 --> 01:01:43,490
And suddenly topics look very different.

613
01:01:43,730 --> 01:01:49,530
And there's a danger of defaulting to this, because the US is sort of the world hegemon, to defaulting to that mindset.

614
01:01:49,780 --> 01:01:52,645
And that's not always the best, most predictive view.

615
01:01:52,645 --> 01:01:53,051
[Temporal Inevitability]

616
01:01:53,051 --> 01:01:54,740
Patrick: Patrick [01:01:53]: We've talked about a lot.

617
01:01:54,990 --> 01:02:00,570
And as we wind down, I'm curious what topic that we haven't talked about at all you are most interested in.

618
01:02:00,570 --> 01:02:06,329
Charlie: Charlie [01:02:01]: Of course, after we finish this, I'll think of tons, but I'm sort of failing to think of anything in the moment.

619
01:02:06,660 --> 01:02:17,920
I think there's one I would pick it would be, and one of the things that's sort of fascinating in sort of the history of tech, is how much startups are temporal inevitabilities.

620
01:02:18,150 --> 01:02:27,720
So as a phrase someone one said to me, what's the difference between a heretic and a prophet in tech, the heretic gets burned at the stake, the prophet becomes famous - about two years.

621
01:02:29,080 --> 01:02:33,729
And you sometimes wonder how much timing matters.

622
01:02:34,080 --> 01:02:46,310
Was a site like Pinterest, always going to exist within a year, that you could download a page of images on the internet in under a hundred milliseconds, was that the sort of temporal inevitability of a product like that?

623
01:02:46,310 --> 01:02:49,520
And is it the same for most products?

624
01:02:49,820 --> 01:02:57,800
For GPS and mobile phone, did that make an Uber like thing inevitable in around 2009, 2010?

625
01:02:58,119 --> 01:02:58,752
One of the greater moments is the temporal one.

626
01:02:58,752 --> 01:03:11,720
And then I think the other sort of great unknown is how much of value is actually created for the top layers of the stack by the bottom layers that don't capture it.

627
01:03:12,110 --> 01:03:14,630
So are we all just the beneficiaries?

628
01:03:14,880 --> 01:03:33,110
Is angel investing just the beneficiary of the emergence of AWS and Azure, because I can tell a story whereby angel investing just didn't exist because it was negative ROIC, because you have spent so much on SUN Microsystems servers and sort of physical equipment that you've just had poor IRR across the whole industry.

629
01:03:33,160 --> 01:03:41,230
Then AWS and Azure come along, and critically as a startup, you don't know your own future demand curve because you don't know what you're going to get put on market fit.

630
01:03:41,940 --> 01:03:46,600
So you either have to buy too many servers in which case you waste capital or too few, in which case you couldn't meet demand.

631
01:03:46,600 --> 01:03:51,620
Whereas with AWS and Azure, they've effectively taken that risk out of the equation.

632
01:03:51,750 --> 01:03:55,149
And you can almost know that your cost base only scales with your success.

633
01:03:55,410 --> 01:03:57,820
Is the entire industry just sitting on that?

634
01:03:57,820 --> 01:04:00,720
Kind of an intuitive feel but it probably is.

635
01:04:01,010 --> 01:04:01,770
Better lucky than good.

636
01:04:01,910 --> 01:04:08,200
Maybe we get an AI boom in the next couple of years, maybe that would be written about as ML.

637
01:04:08,469 --> 01:04:18,460
Maybe it's actually, and Nvidia’s chips and emergence sort of five and seven nanometer nodes, which just drive improvements in throughput that drives ML up.

638
01:04:18,700 --> 01:04:21,390
So it's nothing to do with the companies that are actually working on it.

639
01:04:21,510 --> 01:04:27,219
It's to do with sort of the pickaxes being turned from wood to iron, making their work far more efficient.

640
01:04:27,379 --> 01:04:31,920
And, Nvidia will probably capture some value of that, but probably won't capture the greatest value.

641
01:04:32,050 --> 01:04:47,459
Same if you were to do sort of history of early computing 90s and 2000s, would be interesting to write it from the importance of the evolution of Intel chips and modem speeds as the primary drivers, as opposed to the narrative of history of the growth of these great companies.

642
01:04:47,459 --> 01:04:57,660
Patrick: Patrick [01:04:48]: Well, Charlie, I feel like I could do this with you almost weekly basis, sort of endlessly entertained by your prolific interest in so many different things.

643
01:04:57,830 --> 01:05:02,369
I'll certainly remember this conversation as one, that's a reminder that investing in business are complicated.

644
01:05:02,870 --> 01:05:10,490
And if you want to spend your career in those spaces, you better love it because there are so many variables and so many things happening and you have to develop your own niche and your own strategy.

645
01:05:10,590 --> 01:05:16,410
My closing question for everybody in each of these conversations is to ask for the kindest thing that anyone's ever done for you.

646
01:05:16,410 --> 01:05:20,742
Charlie: Charlie [01:05:17]: Oh my God, there are so many.

647
01:05:20,742 --> 01:05:22,439
There are so many examples.

648
01:05:22,900 --> 01:05:34,534
I think it's probably a recurrent one of often my enthusiasm has been greater than my competence and it's the people that bet on the enthusiasm more than the competence.

649
01:05:34,690 --> 01:05:36,110
I'm internally grateful to them.

650
01:05:36,110 --> 01:05:37,939
Patrick: Patrick [01:05:37]: I love that.

651
01:05:38,080 --> 01:05:40,190
Again, you're sometimes describing my life.

652
01:05:40,190 --> 01:05:42,770
So I know exactly what you mean, and it is a wonderful thing.

653
01:05:42,770 --> 01:05:50,089
And a major category of these answers is betting on somebody early, seeing something in them and taking that risk is always a great kindness.

654
01:05:50,320 --> 01:05:57,239
Well, Charlie, this has been a highlight of my early week, even though it's just Monday, I really appreciate your time and I've loved all your insight.

655
01:05:57,330 --> 01:05:57,670
Thank you.

656
01:06:01,210 --> 01:06:06,380
Charlie: Charlie [01:05:57]: Thank you.

